🚨 REAL-WORLD INCIDENT DEBUGGING SCENARIOS
🧨 Incident 1: Container Keeps Restarting (CrashLoop)
👀 Symptom
docker ps
STATUS: Restarting (1) 5 seconds ago

Or in Kubernetes:

CrashLoopBackOff
🔍 First Step
docker logs <container_id>

You see:

ModuleNotFoundError: No module named 'flask'
🧠 Root Cause

Dependencies not installed

PYTHONPATH not set

Multi-stage copy mistake

✅ Fix

If using multi-stage:

ENV PYTHONPATH="/app/deps"

OR fix COPY:

COPY --from=builder /app/deps /app/deps
🎤 Interview Answer

First I check container logs. If dependencies missing, I verify multi-stage copy and environment variables. Most crashes are due to missing runtime dependencies.

🧨 Incident 2: Works Locally, Fails in Production
👀 Symptom

Local:

docker run -p 5000:5000 works

Production:

Connection refused
🔍 Check
docker inspect <container>

You realize:

App running on:

127.0.0.1
🧠 Root Cause

App bound to localhost.

In container, must bind to:

0.0.0.0
✅ Fix

Flask:

app.run(host="0.0.0.0", port=5000)
🎤 Interview Answer

Container networking requires binding to 0.0.0.0, not localhost. Otherwise external traffic cannot reach the container.

🧨 Incident 3: Permission Denied After Switching to Non-Root
👀 Error
PermissionError: [Errno 13] Permission denied: '/app/logs'
🧠 Root Cause

Files owned by root
Container runs as appuser

✅ Fix
RUN chown -R appuser:appgroup /app
🎤 Interview Answer

When switching to non-root, ownership must be updated using chown, otherwise runtime permission errors occur.

🧨 Incident 4: Port Already in Use
👀 Error
bind: address already in use
🔍 Check
sudo lsof -i :8000
docker ps
🧠 Root Cause

Another container using same port.

✅ Fix

Stop old container or change port mapping.

docker stop <id>
🧨 Incident 5: Image Too Large (1.5GB)
👀 Symptom

Push to registry very slow.

🧠 Root Cause

Using full python image

Not using multi-stage

No .dockerignore

Installing build tools in runtime image

✅ Fix

Use python:slim

Use multi-stage

Use distroless

Add .dockerignore

🎤 Interview Answer

I reduce image size by using multi-stage builds and minimal runtime images like distroless.

🧨 Incident 6: Architecture Mismatch (Very Common Now)
👀 Error
exec format error
🧠 Root Cause

Built on Mac M1 (arm64)
Running on AWS EC2 (amd64)

✅ Fix
docker buildx build --platform linux/amd64 -t myapp .
🎤 Interview Answer

This happens due to architecture mismatch. I solve it using multi-platform build with buildx.

🧨 Incident 7: Container Exits Immediately
👀 docker ps -a
Exited (0) 2 seconds ago
🧠 Root Cause

CMD finished execution.

Example:

CMD ["echo", "hello"]

Container stops after printing.

✅ Fix

Ensure long-running process.

Web server must run in foreground.

🎓 INTERVIEW QUESTIONS — PERFECT ANSWERS
🔹 Difference between Image & Container

Answer:

An image is a read-only blueprint containing application code and dependencies. A container is a running instance of that image with its own writable layer.

🔹 What is Multi-Stage Build?

Multi-stage build allows using multiple FROM statements in one Dockerfile to separate build dependencies from runtime environment, reducing final image size and improving security.

🔹 Why Use Distroless?

Distroless images contain only runtime dependencies without shell or package manager, reducing attack surface and improving security in production.

🔹 What is BuildKit?

BuildKit is Docker’s next-generation build engine that improves caching, performance, parallel execution, and supports advanced features like multi-platform builds.

🔹 What is Non-Root Container?

A container that runs processes as a non-root Linux user, following least privilege principle to reduce security risks.

🔹 Difference Between COPY & ADD?
COPY	ADD
Copies files	Copies + extracts tar + supports URL
Recommended	Avoid unless needed

Interview answer:

I prefer COPY because it is predictable and secure.

🔹 What is Docker Layer Caching?

Docker caches each instruction as a layer. If instruction doesn’t change, Docker reuses cached layer, speeding up builds.

🔹 What is Build Context?

Build context is the directory sent to Docker daemon during build. Docker can only access files inside that context.

🔹 Difference Between CMD & ENTRYPOINT?

CMD provides default arguments, while ENTRYPOINT defines the main executable that always runs.

